Anonymous Fri 03 May 2019 04:49:47 No.22885451 Report
Quoted By: >>22885640 >>22886125 >>22899697
>>22885261
>DNA is just 4 base nucleotide pairs
>therefore mashing genes together can't go too wrong
The difference between sickle cell anemia and a healthy red blood cell is a single switched codon. It's the same way with most genetic diseases, ranging from the inconvenient to the lethal. A single error produces Bad Shit, and without perfect knowledge of how the human body works (which I assure you we absolutely do not have) there's no way to tell for sure how a single new gene will interact with the incredibly myriad processes that accompany mere homeostasis, much less the far more complex developmental factors that govern how the body develops from an embryo.
The only way to find out is to test it in reality, and see if the result dies, lives in torment, or survives to flourish. The last one is much less likely the more you introduce stuff that screws with body structure. As much as I'd love to have scalies running around, it's not going to be in my lifetime.

Anonymous Fri 03 May 2019 05:28:06 No.22886125 Report
Quoted By:
>>22885451
DNA exists because it's 'polymorphic', in a sense. It can edit itself, enable and disable segments within itself, and experience random mutations from environmental factors and cell division. Beyond the control segments that facilitate that behavior, DNA is really just a 1-to-1 representation of proteins that should be manufactured, and under what conditions.

So the real problem is disassembling your desired outcome into a protein systems problem. That's... very hard. There's millions, probably billions of different interactions, and you have to be careful not to interfere with any of that. To do this, you'll need to be able to fold proteins, which is already a hard problem, as well as simulate the entire system.

Humanity will never get anywhere by just sticking genes together and hoping for the best. At some point, we'll be bottlenecked by the lack of simulation capabilities, and simply by the fact that the protein systems will grow exponentially more complex as the complexity of your desired behavior grows.

It's likely that we'll never understand how it works on our own. The system is just too complicated. Limited simulations, introducing random targeted mutations to the protein system, might be the only way of getting what we want. We would be leveraging a type of machine learning to make the changes and drive the system towards the desired behavior, but we wouldn't understand the results any more than evolution understands what it created. It'd pretty much be artificial evolution in a sense.
